Wash and dry all produce. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2%unit}, separating whites from greens. Halve, peel, and dice @yellow onion{1%unit}. Core, deseed, and dice @poblano pepper{1%unit} into ½-inch pieces.

Melt @butter{1%tablespoon} in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add scallion whites; cook, stirring occasionally, until softened, ~{1%minute}. Add @jasmine rice{1/2%cup}, ¾ cup water, and a big pinch of @salt{}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

Heat a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%teaspoon} in a #medium pot{} over medium-high heat. Add onion and poblano; cook, stirring occasionally, until slightly softened, ~{4-6%minutes}. Add @tomato paste{1.5%ounce}, @Southwest spice blend{1%tablespoon}, @Mexican spice blend{1%tablespoon}, and @salt{1%tsp}. Season generously with @pepper{}. Cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> Use 2 tsp salt for 4 servings instead of 1 tsp.

Stir @diced tomatoes{14%ounce}, @veggie stock concentrate{1%unit}, @kidney beans{13.4%ounce} and their liquid, and ½ cup water into pot. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to medium. Simmer until thickened, ~{15-18%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper to taste.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, combine @sour cream{2%tablespoon} and half the @hot sauce{1%teaspoon}. Add water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.

> Add more hot sauce if you like things spicy.

Fluff rice with a #fork{} and season with salt. Divide between #bowls{} and top with chili.

> Alternatively, you can serve chili on the side if you like.

Garnish with @Mexican cheese blend{1/2%cup}, scallion greens, and hot sauce crema. Serve.